Data Visualization in Python using FastFood Restaurants Dataset of US¶


1. Problem Statement¶

This dataset is a list of hundreds of thousands of fast food restaurants across USA. We need to make some analysis on this dataset so that we can draw some useful inferences.

2. Loading Packages and Dataset¶

2.1 Importing Packages¶

We will be inserting all the necessary packages for analysis.

In [1]:

3.1 Pre-Profiling¶

In [10]:
profile = pandas_profiling.ProfileReport(fastfood_restaurant_data)
profile.to_file(output_file="fastfood_restaurant_data_before_preprocessing.html")

From the pre-profiling, we find the below observations:

  • Summary of the datatypes:
    • Numerical: latitude,longitude
    • Categorical: address,city,country,keys,name,postal code,province,websites.
  • Country column has constant value as US.
  • Websites has missing values.
  • Keys column has all the unique values.
  • The names of the restaurants are case sensitive i.e same restaurant name in capital letters is treated different from the restaurant name in small letters.

Pre-processing¶

Dropping the column country as the whole dataset belongs to the country US.

In [11]:
fastfood_restaurant_data.drop('country', axis = 1,inplace = True)
print(fastfood_restaurant_data.columns)

       'postalCode', 'province', 'websites'],
      dtype='object')

In [15]:
restaurant_names = fastfood_restaurant_data['name'].unique()
import nltk
most_similar = []
for i in range(len(restaurant_names)):
    temp_similar = [restaurant_names[i]]
    for j in range(len(restaurant_names)):
        if restaurant_names[i] == restaurant_names[j]:
            continue
        if nltk.edit_distance(restaurant_names[i].lower(), restaurant_names[j].lower()) < 3:
            temp_similar.append(restaurant_names[j])
        if len(temp_similar) > 1:
            most_similar.append(temp_similar)
most_similar_word_count = 0
for i in most_similar:
      most_similar_word_count += len(i)
print("size of the most similar list:", most_similar_word_count)

size of the most similar list: 140483

def percent_more_than_1_restaurants_city(list_restaurants,city):
    more_than_1_restaurants = list_restaurants[list_restaurants > 1]
    percent_more_than_1_restaurants = round(len(more_than_1_restaurants)/sum(list_restaurants)*100,2)
    print("City "+city+ " has "+ str(percent_more_than_1_restaurants)+ "% of total fastfood restaurants more than 1 restaurant open.")
          
percent_more_than_1_restaurants_city(restaurants, "Cincinnati")
percent_more_than_1_restaurants_city(restaurants1, "Las Vegas")
percent_more_than_1_restaurants_city(restaurants2, "Houston")

City Cincinnati has 10.92% of total fastfood restaurants more than 1 restaurant open.
City Las Vegas has 25.0% of total fastfood restaurants more than 1 restaurant open.
City Houston has 17.46% of total fastfood restaurants more than 1 restaurant open.

def plot_donut_chart(city_name):
    data = fastfood_restaurant_data[fastfood_restaurant_data["city"]== city_name]
    counts =  data["names"].value_counts()[:10]
    space = np.ones(10)/10
    counts.plot(kind='pie', explode=space, fontsize=14, autopct='%3.1f%%', wedgeprops=dict(width=0.15), 
                                       shadow=True, startangle=160, figsize=(10,10), cmap='inferno', legend=True)
    plt.ylabel('')
    plt.title("Spread of fastfood restaurants in "+ city_name,fontsize=18,fontweight="bold") 
    plt.show()

plot_donut_chart("Cincinnati")
plot_donut_chart("Las Vegas")
plot_donut_chart("Houston")

5.Inferences/Conclusions:¶

The fast food restaurant dataset helps us understand the spread of fastfood restaurants spread across US by province and by city. We found some more interesting facts as follows:

  1. Mc Donald's is the most prevailed fast food restaurant across US (or) Mc Donald's is the King of fast food restaurants.(#section 4.1)
  2. Calfornia,Texas and Ohio provinces has the most fast food restaurants where as Colorado Springs has the least.(#section 4.3)
  3. Cities Cincinnati,Las Vegas and Houston has the most fast food restaurants and they have 10.92%,25.0%,17.46% of total fastfood restaurants more than 1 restaurant open respectively.Cincinnati is the fast food capital of US. (#section 4.6)
  4. Cincinnati has the largest number of Mc Donald's restaurants.(#section 4.2)
  5. More than 70% of the cities have 1-4 fastfood restaurants and only 20 % cities have more than 5 restaurants.(#section 4.9)
  6. 44.8% of the cities in US has only 1 fast food restaurant.(#section 4.8)
  7. Mostly central and southern provinces of the US have more number of fast food restaurants.(#section 4.1.0)
  8. Number of restaurants are proportional to the population in that province.Cities with the fewest fast food restaurants per capita are mainly concentrated in the Northeast of US.(#section 4.1.3)
